`contains()` method uses `equals()` method to check if an object is in the list. If you haven&#39;t overridden the `equals()` method in your `Product` class, it will use the one from `Object`, which only returns true if the two objects are the same object in memory. You need to override the `equals()` method in your `Product` class to define what makes two `Product` objects equal.

example:

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        if (this == obj)
            return true;
        if (obj == null)
            return false;
        if (getClass() != obj.getClass())
            return false;
        Product other = (Product) obj;
        if (attribute == null) {
            if (other.attribute != null)
                return false;
        } else if (!attribute.equals(other.attribute))
            return false;
        return true;
    }


Once you implement `equals()` its recomended to also override the `hashCode()` method. If you don&#39;t do so, equal objects may get different hashes, and hash based collections (`HashMap`, `HashSet`, ..) will not work properly.

Override the _equals_ and _hashCode_ methods of _Product_, pointing them to the unique attribute.

Additionally, _sub-class_ _ArrayList_, and _override_ the _contains_ method.

Here is an example.

```java
record Product(String s) {
    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        return s.equals(((Product) obj).s);
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return s.hashCode();
    }
}
List&lt;Product&gt; ps = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;() {
    @Override
    public boolean contains(Object o) {
        for (Product p : this)
            if (p.s.equals(o)) return true;
        return false;
    }
};
ps.add(new Product(&quot;abc&quot;));
ps.add(new Product(&quot;123&quot;));
System.out.println(ps.contains(&quot;xyz&quot;));
System.out.println(ps.contains(&quot;123&quot;));
```

