# Override `equals` 

The [Answer by Reilas][1] is good. Overriding [`Object#equals`][2] is key here. But a couple notes:

 - Subclassing `ArrayList` seems a bit extreme just to do a `contains`. Unnecessary after overriding `equals`. 
 - Alternate syntax is possible, using [`Objects`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Objects.html) utility class.

I see no need to subclass [`ArrayList`][3]. The [`List`][4] interface defines a [`contains`][5] method, and `ArrayList` already contains a proper implementation. 

Below is some similar example code. The `equals` &amp; `hashCode` implementations were [generated by IntelliJ][6] [IDE][7]. 

Important: When overriding either `equals` or `hashCode`, **always override both**, using consistent logic.

Define your class as a [record][8] if its main purpose is to transparently communicate shallowly-immutable data. Note that a `record` can be defined locally, as seen here. (Ditto for `interface` and `enum` in Java 16+, by the way.)

